#Model3- Group discussion 
8a.  When reviewing our table creation scripts, we noticed several differences in how each of us implemented the database design. All three scripts included the same core tables (Customers, Dogs, Walks, and Payments), but the structure and level of detail varied.
My script and Dahlia’s script followed a similar approach, where each walk is associated with a single dog through a foreign key. However, Destiney’s script introduced a junction table (Walk_Dogs), allowing a many-to-many relationship between walks and dogs. This makes her design more flexible, as multiple dogs can be assigned to a single walk. We also differed in how we handled constraints. Dahlia included features like AUTO_INCREMENT, CHECK constraints, UNIQUE, and ON DELETE CASCADE to improve data integrity. My script used AUTO_INCREMENT and foreign keys but fewer constraints, making it simpler. Destiney’s script was the most minimal, without AUTO_INCREMENT or validation constraints. These differences were driven by choices between simplicity, flexibility, and data integrity.
8b. After running each other’s scripts from the shared repository, we observed that executing a different script replaces the existing schema because of the DROP SCHEMA and CREATE SCHEMA commands. This allowed us to test and better understand how each database design works in practice. However, it also meant that our own schema was overwritten when running someone else’s script. To restore our original version, we had to rerun our own script. This process helped us understand how schema management works and highlighted the importance of being careful when working with shared database scripts.
